n this collection also take the manifestations of pop culture as serious objects of academic study, and investigate, among other things, the origin of the vampire as medial phenomenon with ethnological and sociological methods, or test the ubiquitous scenes of apocalypse in film and TV with material and philosophic analyses. It becomes clear that quality and popularity need not necessarily run contrary to one another.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn German.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aArtsxHistory. 0aPopular culture. 4aCultural Studies. 4aFilmanalyse. 4aInterdisziplinarität. 4aKulturwissenschaft. 4aLiteraturwissenschaft. 4aMedienanalyse. 4aMedienästhetik. 4aPopkultur. 4aSprachwissenschaft. 4aWissenschaft. 4aWissenschaftssoziologie. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Popular Culture.2bisacsh  aCultural Studies.  aInterdisciplinarity.  aLinguistics.  aLiterary Studies.  aMedia Aesthetics.  aScience.  aSociology of Science.1 aBrandes, Sonja, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOhlendorf, Wiebke, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOhlendorf, Wiebke, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aReichart, André, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aReichart, André, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSchmidtchen, Gunnar, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchmidtchen, Gunnar, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aStein, Christian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStrahl, Alexander, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWermbter, Katja, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aZappi, Timo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb